This paper deals with the complexity of scheduling problems, which is a fundamental topic in computer science. The paper uses techniques from algorithms, optimization, and complexity theory. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), which is the primary area for scheduling problems. The paper also deals with information theory (cs.IT) since it considers the k-norm of flow and stretch schedules. Additionally, the paper uses techniques from machine learning (cs.LG) to analyze the complexity of the scheduling problem. The paper also deals with discrete mathematics (cs.DM) since it uses combinatorial techniques to analyze the scheduling problem. Finally, the paper deals with computer communication (cs.CC) since scheduling is a critical issue in network communication.
